Climate oppositions inhibited the economy
In the first year of Mario López Valdez's government, unemployment and black work increased in Sinaloa, while foreign investment fell and the economy stagnated.
In 2011, Sinaloas will be remembered in the economic history. It is the first year Mario López Valdez, who is calling himself the initiator of transformation and has created great hopes for economic growth. However, as a result of the climate-wide oppositions, growth cannot be mentioned, but, on the contrary, the most important economic indicators deteriorated.
The low temperatures in February caused not only losses in millions in agriculture, but also limited the growth of the state economy and resulted in a general decline in economic activity by 3.6 percent in the first quarter of the year, mainly in the historical decline in agricultural development by 31.16 percent, which has been inevitably affected by further economic sectors.
According to a report published by the Consejo Mexicano para el Desarrollo Rural Sustentable (Mexican Council for Sustainable Agricultural Development), 582 000 hectares of agricultural lands used were damaged, of which 78.03 percent were completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07 percent were partially destroyed.
The decline in economic activity by November has constantly increased unemployment in the Mexican state. The Instituteo Nacional de Estadística y Geografía observed a rapid increase in unemployment in the first quarter of the year, since from January to March 55 053 inhabitants had no employment, which corresponds to 4.53 percent of the labour force. In the second quarter, the unemployment rate rose to 5.28 percent and from July to September to 6.19 percent, resulting in 74 000 unemployed in Sinaloa.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa in the year is due to several factors. The economic scientist Gerardo López Cervantes, dean of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the University of Autónoma (UAS), commented that the public institutions' policy indirect explains the growing unemployment.
"What we are currently observing is an increase in unemployment, which has to do with several factors. Among other things, with liquidity losses on the market due to the medium reductions by the legislation adopted to combat money laundering at the Congress, because for those who collect dollars forbidden it is not easy to let them work for themselves, invest them or use something else," he explained.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that growing unemployment is also a demographic factor.
"The number of people leaving the country in search of work abroad, especially in the United States, has declined, on the one hand due to the problems of entry and on the other, because it is difficult to find work there too. These people stay here and look for work, which causes unemployment to rise," he said.
Blackwork
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is even more serious, taking into account the high proportion of blackwork, which, according to INEGI, covers 60.38 percent of those working in the country without paying into the social insurance cash.
Unemployment and black work are the lowest wages, the lowest in all of Mexico, according to the statistics of the Instituteo Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexican Social Insurance Institute) and the Secretariat del Trabajo y Previsión Social (Regulationsbehörde für Arbeit und soziale Fürsorge in Mexico).
The average monthly income of employees in Sinaloa was by September 5352 pesos, which is much less than the general government average of 7375 pesos.
Decline of the ADI
In addition to decreasing economic activity and growing unemployment, in 2011 the strongest decline in foreign direct investment (ADI) in the past ten years is recorded. According to Secretaría de Economía (State Economic Authority), the ADI was $630 597 from January to June, which corresponds to a sweat of 87.74 percent compared to the $5143 312 in the same period of the previous year.
Sectaría de Desarrollo Económico del Gobierno (Regulation for Economic Development) has a total investment of 17 280 000 pesos in 2011, most of which comes from companies from the tertiary sector.
Debts
In view of the economic crisis, the national government requested a loan of 3 000 000 000 pesos in July to reactivate the economy in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities. The National Congress approved a amount of 200 600 000 pesos, but no positive impact of debt on any of the country's industries could be identified by November.
Reactions
For the entrepreneurship representatives, the first year of Mario López Valdé’s incapability of government made it clear.
Miguel Loredo López, Chairman of the Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación (State Chamber of Processing Industry in Mexico), stated that in 2011 no effort was made to harmonize the views of the different sectors, including the national government.
"The economic activity in Sinaloa was really in need of work this year. It has to be worked hard to recover the terrain lost this year and we have to double effort in 2012. The efforts of all, and in particular, the progress of the already well agreed government team, have not been sufficiently coordinated together," he said.
Slow economic development
Loredo López said that events, as frost at the beginning of the year, made the country’s economic development difficult and slower.
"The low economic flow is the result of several events, including frost. One of the main effects is a slowed economy that is not enough in motion to create an economic dynamic which could create an acceptable flow of processes, products and services. Therefore we will finish the year far below our expectations," he said.
Re-defining vocation
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, Chairman of the Confederación Patronal de la República Mexicana (entrepreneurship association of Mexico) in Sinaloa, stated that the state had to be more dynamic.
"In general, we have observed that work has been done. We believe it is necessary to develop a long-term programme to re-determine the economic profession and line of the country, because it is important to activate all material and human resources Sinaloas," he said.
There is a lot to do
The Chairman of Coparmex stressed the importance of developing a future perspective that guides government efforts in better ways.
"In general, I would say that the government has achieved good results in various areas. Economic development has progressed, but it is important to develop a long-term programme," he said.
He stressed that the current state power had made progress with the government.
"There are areas in which one can say that the government has acted more extensively. What I can say is that has been worked and that the government is aware that there is still a lot of work ahead of it," he said.
