The Court approves the transition to the digital television in Mexico for 2015
The conversion of analogues to digital signals has been one of the most important changes worldwide in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) rejected the constitutional complaints lodged by the Senate and the House of Deputies against the Bureau’s Decree and, in effect, the transfer of analogue to digital signals from 2021 to 2015, due to the lack of eight votes required for the fight against law.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Supreme Court, Juan Silva Meza, was of the opinion that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his responsibilities when he issued the Decree of Law with details on the transition to terrestrial digital television.
This decision rejected the constitutional dispute initiated by the Senate, since it did not receive the necessary qualified majority of eight votes so that the court could decide on constitutionality or non-Constitutionality.
The project for the complaint drawn up by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero suggested that the Decree of Law should be declared inadmissible, as the Comisión Federal de Telecomunicaciones (Cofetel) (Federal Commission for Telecommunications in Mexico) is responsible for the regulations relating to radio and television, and therefore the Decree of Law would contradict the hierarchical principles and the law reserved.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted for the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies submitted constitutional complaints against the Decree of Law. Following the adoption of the complaints, the Minister Sánchez Cordero no longer applied the Decree of Law and introduced all activities to establish digital transmission.
The Council of Ministers also rejected the complaint filed by the Chamber of Deputies, without entering into the debate on the project for which Minister Sánchez Cordero was also responsible.
In his contribution, the Prime Minister said that he should not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the national government cannot regulate the measures to be taken by public administration by general rules.
"I also do not believe that if this was done, the independence of the regulatory body would be affected."It also reminded that the central government is responsible for planning strategic policies, such as the telecommunications sector, for constitutional reasons, because it is the leader of state affairs.
The replacement of analog signals by digital is one of the most important changes that have taken place in recent years around the world, and it improves the use of radioelectric spectrum, an increased quality of the signal and more channels.
The postponement of the changeover, she said, was a postponement of the use of digitization, which is a decision in public interest that does not only have technical aspects, "because they cover economic, social, political and security aspects."
These issues, she stressed, "required the action of the entire system, in accordance with the principle of economic governance by the State they included a group of features that lay the Constitution into the hands of the central government."
She recalled that many countries around the world had already carried out digital conversion, although they had highly specialized institutions.
It could not be concluded that the government would enter into the competences of the Congress with the release of the contested Decree of Law, because the laws adopted by the Legislative would comply," she assured.
The possibility to count the votes in Michoacán individually is considered
According to PREP, the difference between the first and the second place in the election of the governor is nearly 27 percent, with 879 votes from a total of 6074 not yet counted.
The possibility of the single counting of the vote records this year is a reality in the elections in Michoacán, because according to the data issued by the Programa de Resultados Electorales Preliminares (PREP), the difference between the first and second place in the governor elections is nearly 27 percent, with 879 votes from a total of 6074 not yet counted.
In this sense, the President of the Consejo General del Instituto Electoral de Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, reminded that just last 9 November, the election body had adopted a number of rules for harmonising local regulations with the reforms of the state in electoral affairs.
It should be recalled that Michoacán had neither adapted his political constitution nor his election law nor his law on election justice to the reforms adopted by the Congress, so that they had not entered into force at this election round. Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel avoided their publication in the State Advisory Board within the time limits for that purpose with the argument or objections to it.
On 9 November, the Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) decided on the constitutional complaint lodged by the local legislature and judged the prosecutor's vote on constitutional reforms as "invaluable and illegal", since it does not have the right to "determine or impose a veto on it".
María de los Ángeles Llanderal explained in an interview on the possibility of a single countdown of the votes that thanks to the adoption of the directives by the Consejo General del IEM, the local electoral authority would now be able to count the vote records partially or completely.
The results of the protocols cannot be partially counted under the following conditions: the protocol on the counting and calculation of votes is not available or there is no possession of the Chairman of the Committee of Elections or there are obvious mistakes or amendments in the protocols.
In addition, the total counting of the entirely filled election documents may be made if there is a difference between the alleged winner and the one standing at second place, equal or less than one percent, provided that at the beginning of the meeting an explicit request is made by the party-or-severe coalition chairman, which is the second of those candidates.
The counting of votes may also take place in its entirety, if, after the conclusion of the proper calculation, it is found that the difference between the suspected winner and the candidate is equal or less than one percent at the second place, provided that an explicit application is provided by a representative of the party whose candidate has become second. In this case, the choice packages exposed to a partial countdown would be excluded.
It is worth mentioning that the elections in Morelia are in the same situation, where, according to PREP, the difference between the first and second place is nearly 0.16 percent, although the votes of 129 of a total of 923 election protocols have not yet been counted.
