The designated Prime Minister, Mario Monti, meets tomorrow with the President of Italy to present to this the new government which is supposed to present the crisis that has led Italy to the margin of economic collapse.
A communication from the presidency palace announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, would meet with the President-in-Office of State, Giorgio Napolitano, to confirm governmental education.
It is assumed that he will present a cabinet composed by a majority of technocrates, although it is not yet clear when the new Prime Minister will take up his office.
Monti said that he would present to the President the results of the discussions with the political parties on the formation of government.
"I would like to reaffirm my absolute confidence in the ability of our country to deal with these difficult times," said the former EU Commissioner to journalists.
Monti did not expressly confirm governmental education, but his comments indicate that the obstacles have been overcome.
The "frame is now well cut", he added.
Monti has managed to form a government in less than three days, which is much less time than normal. At the same time, Italy is fighting against a political and financial crisis that has driven the cost of debt into an incomparable amount.
The new government, led by the former EU Commissioner Monti, must adopt a hard saving package, which was required by the euro politicians to regain the confidence in Italy.
The pressure on the hurry on Monti was still intensified by the fluctuating market situation, as a result of which Italian government bonds were taxed with 7 percent interest for 10 years. This corresponds to the situation in which Greece and Ireland were forced to apply for the European rescue screen.
