Asphalt from UNAM prevents stroke holes
Rafael Herrera, researchers at the Faculty of Chemistry at the University of Mexico, UNAM developed asphalts modified with polymers to make the mix more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
If it were not necessary to repair nearly 200 000 stroke holes when the rainy season in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (city of the valley of Mexico) erupted, Rafael Herrera Najera, researchers at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at the University of UNAM, warned and assured that if the interpretation and maintenance of the asphalt bearing are adequately seen, the number of stroke holes will be significantly reduced or even completely avoided.
In his lecture "Bagholes from a technical point of view", which he held on chemistry at the International Year, he announced that the laboratory, for which he is responsible, develops asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture similar to the asphalt, which, however, has a greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Najera said that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climate, such as in some cities in the northern part of the country, to improve the behaviour of the street cover and thus avoid the occurrence of stroke holes.
He explained that the asphalt - the most serious part of the oil - is a hydrocarbon compound, of which part has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphalts - and the other part a low - the so-called malthene. Together they give to the street cover its characteristic teethic behaviour.
The weighty behaviour of the asphalt means that at high temperatures of nearly 180°C it is like a liquid, at 120°C it is very tough and nearly fixed at 50°C, while it becomes brew at very low temperatures.
"This means that the resistance of the asphalt on the streets is not uniform, but changes on a day depending on the weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," the chemical engineer reported.
The researcher of the FQ noted that the streets of Mexico City had mostly a flexible street cover consisting of six material layers, of which the last three asphalts were included.
Between the top layers lies a wear layer of asphalt that consists of small, in asphalt fried and then fixed stones.
Each single stone of this wear layer, had been bathed in asphalt.
When the vehicles are moving on and producing forces, this layer enables a good distribution of power in the street cover.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would spread even better," said the chemical engineer.
"Over the wear layer," he stated, "a last layer is designed, the so-called drag layer consisting of tiny stones, i.e. sand, which was also bathed in asphalt.
Since this layer is in contact with the vehicle tyres, they need a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and must produce friction.
This road cover receives and distributes most of the forces, the load layer also needs an appropriate thickness and the material it consists of must be maintained.
The weather conditions, in particular humidity and temperature fluctuations, are other, important factors to be taken into account, above all the water," he said, "because it significantly affects the behaviour of the wear layer.
When the site is wet, water penetrates into the layer and is only difficult to escape. This causes an eradication of all layers of the street cover and consequently the appearance of stroke holes.
